{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012S8KXSnytHDXsdwGQDLMYS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the issue. The configmap `es-config` is missing `cluster.initial_master_nodes`. This is a Elasticsearch 7.x requirement for bootstrapping a brand-new cluster.\n\nHere's my plan:\n1. **Phase 1 - Add bootstrap setting**: Patch the `es-config` configmap to add `cluster.initial_master_nodes: [\"es-cluster-0\", \"es-cluster-1\", \"es-cluster-2\"]`\n2. **Restart pods** so they pick up the new config (since the configmap is mounted as a subPath, it doesn't auto-update)\n3. **Wait for cluster to form**: Monitor until the cluster is healthy with a master elected\n4. **Phase 2 - Remove bootstrap setting**: Once the cluster has formed and a cluster UUID is established, patch the configmap to remove `cluster.initial_master_nodes`\n5. **Rolling restart**: Delete pods one at a time, waiting for each to rejoin and the cluster to stabilize before moving to the next\n\nThe key insight is that `cluster.initial_master_nodes` is only needed for the initial bootstrapping of a fresh cluster. Once it's formed and has a persistent identity, the setting becomes unnecessary.\n\nSince the config is mounted as a subPath, ConfigMap changes won't automatically propagate to running pods—I'll need to restart them to pick up the new configuration. Let me start by adding `cluster.initial_master_nodes` to the configmap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1906,"cache_read_input_tokens":34546,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1906},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0715adff-902c-41dc-a396-8ac05bd18717","uuid":"5df27a9a-e19e-45d9-afbf-c5f